        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>* Justification of selected band, angular resolution, sensitivity

The science goal is to image the circum-nuclear distribution of cold dust in the torus around NGC1068, a nearby AGN. Band 9, with a baseband frequency 684 GHz, central wavelength 440mu, is an absolute necessity (440mu correspond to a thermal temperature of just 7 K.)

We simulated the source for a wide range of parameters, and determined that it will not exceed 0.992 arcsec angular diameter in the sky. 1/3 of the field-of-view of the 12-m array corresponds to 3.07 arcsec, thus a single pointing of the array will suffice. Our simulations also show that at the other end of the parameter spectrum, the source won't be smaller than approximately 0.25 arcsec. Under all circumstances we will achieve the science goal!

To resolve the brightness distribution as required by the science
goal, ALMA's highest angular resolution for the 12-m array in band 9, is required, i.e. 0.09 arcsec. From SED fitting of available
high-angular resolution data in the NIR &amp; MIR domains, and one SMA
measurement at 1 mm, we estimate the total continuum source flux
density at 440mu to be ~106 mJy. With 0.992 arcsec source diameter,
and 0.09 beam size, the mean flux density per beam is 0.873 mJy/beam. 5-sigma sensitivity limit is then ~0.1745 mJy. The OT, and
the ALMA Sensitivity Calculator then estimate a total observing time
until science goal is reached of 4.93h, with 1.88h spent on-source. We note that our proposed observations can be carried out in blocks, as weather and technical considerations demand.

* Justification for selecting NGC1068 to achieve the science goal

NGC1068 as the ideal target for the torus size estimation. It is one
of the brightest and closest AGN, thus offers a relatively large
angular size in the sky. It is probably the best-studied AGN,
especially in the Infrared. Comparison of the sub-mm data obtained
with this proposal to the various mid-IR observations will enable
constraints on dust and temperature distributions, morphology, etc.

We selected NGC1068 over a closer source, Circinus. While closer (4
Mpc) to Earth than NGC1068 (14.4 Mpc), Circinus' black hole is 10
times less massive, and consequently its luminosity is also much lower (estimated at 10e44 erg/s by Tristram+2007). NGC1068's luminosity is not well established (1 to 3e45 erg/s), but is at least an order of magnitude higher than in Circinus. The effects of luminosity and closeness on the angular size of the two AGNs almost balance out, with slight advantage for NGC1068.

More importantly, however, are results from VLTI observations of both AGN in the MIR. Jaffe+2004 &amp; Raban+2009 observed NGC1068, and
Tristram+2007 Circinus. These observations resolved the MIR emission
from a few central parsecs around both AGN, but while in NGC1068 they revealed the signature of very hot dust emission, Circinus notably lacks this hot component. This is a sign that the circum-nuclear dust reservoir in Circinus might be much poorer, and whatever dust is there is not heated by the low luminosity levels. In the outer torus, where the 440mu photons are emitted, the intensity will be much lower in Circinus than in NGC1068, and might not reach the sensitivity limit of ALMA. We therefore expect NGC1068 to be the better candidate for the task at hand: measuring the extension of cool dust emission in an AGN torus.

In addition, Circinus is on the Cycle-1 duplicate list; regardless of what the Circinus proposal reveals, it is prudent to compare the
sub-mm properties of these two active galaxies, especially in light of their so different IR signatures. NGC1068, together with Circinus, are probably the only two AGN suitable for measuring the torus size with ALMA.

Data of NGC1068 from Cycle-0 are present in the public archive, but
they do not have the required resolution nor sensitivity to achieve
our science goal. The capabilities required for our science goal are
only now available, for the first time, with Cycle 2.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
