    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose band 9 continuum observations, extended configuration, to
image the dusty AGN torus in NGC1068 in its entirety. NGC1068 is the
ideal source for this task: it is close to Earth, luminous, a
prototypical type-2 active galaxy, and one of the best-studied
AGN. The proposed observations will settle a 25-year old question: how
big are AGN tori? While the torus innermost region has been resolved
in NGC1068 with VLTI at mid-IR wavelengths, its outer extension is, as
in all AGN so far, entirely unknown. The torus material might
originate as accretion disc winds, or in an opposite scenario as
infalling gas clouds on their way to feed the black hole. Since the
internal structure and extent of the torus are unknown, it is
currently impossible to determine its origin and therefore its role as
feeding/feedback mechanism. With the proposed observations we will
also be able to rule decisively if clumpy (compact scales) or
smooth-density tori (much larger scales required) are the
reality. ALMA's revolutionary capabilities and the Cycle-2 combination
of available baselines and sensitivity provide the very first
opportunity to achieve the proposed objective.</prp:abstract>
